16 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
17 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
18 Article – Environment
19 1–307.
20 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “MARKET CAPITALIZATION” MEANS THE TOTAL
21 MARKET VALUE OF A COMPANY’S OUTSTANDING SHARES OF STOCK.
22 (B) FOR THE PROTECTION OF THE HEALTH AND SAFETY OF THE STATE’S
23 CITIZENS AND ENVIRONMENT, IT IS THE INTENT OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY THAT
24 A PUBLICLY TRADED ENTITY, INCLUDING ITS SUBSIDIARIES, WITH A CUMULATIVE
25 MARKET CAPITALIZATION GREATER THAN $1,000,000,000 THAT IS OR WAS
26 INVOLVED IN EXTRACTING, REFINING, OR PROCESSING COAL, OIL, OR GAS BE HELD
27 ACCOUNTABLE FOR ANY TORTIOUS OR OTHERWISE UNLAWFUL CONDUCT ON THE
28 PART OF THE ENTITY OR SUBSIDIARY THAT HAS CONTRIBUTED TO CLIMATE
29 CHANGE, INCLUDING ASSOCIATED ENVIRONMENTAL AND OTHER HARMS CAUSED,
30 WHETHER THROUGH FRAUD, DECEPTION, OR ANY OTHER MECHANISM, ACTION,
31 INACTION, OR PRACTICE.
32 (C) THE ATTORNEY GENERAL MAY INVESTIGATE, COMMENCE, AND
33 PROSECUTE OR DEFEND ANY CIVIL OR CRIMINAL SUIT OR ACTION THAT HOLDS
34 ACCOUNTABLE A PUBLICLY TRADED ENTITY, INCLUDING ITS SUBSIDIARIES, WITH A
35 CUMULATIVE MARKET CAPITALIZATION GREATER THAN $1,000,000,000 AT THE
36 TIME A SUIT OR AN ACTION IS FILED THAT IS OR WAS INVOLVED IN EXTRACTING,
37 REFINING, OR PROCESSING COAL, OIL, OR GAS FOR ANY TORTIOUS OR OTHERWISE

SENATE BILL 432 3
1 UNLAWFUL CONDUCT ON THE PART OF THE ENTITY OR SUBSIDIARY THAT HAS
2 CONTRIBUTED TO CLIMATE CHANGE THROUGH FRAUD, DECEPTION, OR ANY OTHER
3 MECHANISM, ACTION, INACTION, OR PRACTICE.
4 (D) THE ATTORNEY GENERAL MAY HIRE OUTSIDE COUNSEL TO ASSIST
5 WITH AN ACTION UNDER THIS SECTION IF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL DETERMINES
6 THAT HIRING OUTSIDE COUNSEL IS IN THE BEST INTEREST OF THE STATE.
7 (E) THE PROVISIONS OF § 6–106.2 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE
8 SHALL APPLY TO ANY ACTION BROUGHT BY THE ATTORNEY GENERAL UNDER THIS
9 SECTION.
10 Article – Public Safety
11 SUBTITLE 14. CLIMATE CRIMES ACCOUNTABILITY FUND.
12 14–1401.
13 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
14 INDICATED.
15 (B) “FUND” MEANS THE CLIMATE CRIMES ACCOUNTABILITY FUND.
16 (C) “SALTWATER INTRUSION” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 3–1001 OF
17 THE NATURAL RESOURCES ARTICLE.
18 (D) “VECTORBORNE PATHOGEN” MEANS A GERM OR PARASITE THAT IS
19 SPREAD TO HUMANS AND OTHER ANIMALS BY A VECTOR, SUCH AS A MOSQUITO,
20 TICK, OR FLEA.
21 (E) “WATERBORNE PATHOGEN” MEANS A MICROORGANISM, SUCH AS
22 BACTERIA, A VIRUS, A PARASITE, OR AN AMOEBA, THAT CAN CAUSE ILLNESS IN
23 HUMANS AND ANIMALS IF EXPOSED TO WATER CONTAMINATED BY THE
24 MICROORGANISM.
25 14–1402.
26 (A) THERE IS A CLIMATE CRIMES ACCOUNTABILITY FUND.
27 (B) THE PURPOSE OF THE FUND IS TO PAY FOR PROGRAMS THAT PREVENT,
28 MITIGATE, OR REPAIR HARMS CAUSED BY CLIMATE CHANGE.
29 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADMINISTER THE FUND.

4 SENATE BILL 432
1 (D) (1) THE FUND IS A SPECIAL, NONLAPSING FUND THAT IS NOT
2 SUBJECT TO § 7–302 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
3 (2) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL HOLD THE FUND SEPARATELY,
4 AND THE COMPTROLLER SHALL ACCOUNT FOR THE FUND.
5 (E) THE FUND CONSISTS OF:
6 (1) ALL REVENUES RECEIVED BY THE STATE RESULTING DIRECTLY
7 OR INDIRECTLY FROM ANY JUDGMENT AGAINST OR SETTLEMENT WITH AN ENTITY
8 IN AN ACTION BROUGHT UNDER § 1–307 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE;
9 (2) INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND; AND
10 (3) ANY OTHER MONEY FROM ANY OTHER SOURCE ACCEPTED FOR
11 THE BENEFIT OF THE FUND.
12 (F) THE FUND MAY BE USED ONLY TO:
13 (1) PAY FOR PROGRAMS THAT PREVENT, MITIGATE, OR REPAIR
14 HARMS CAUSED BY CLIMATE CHANGE, INCLUDING PROGRAMS ADDRESSING:
15 (I) AIR POLLUTION;
16 (II) DANGEROUSLY HIGH TEMPERATURES, SUCH AS URBAN
17 HEAT ISLANDS OR EXTENDED HEAT WAVES;
18 (III) DROUGHT;
19 (IV) ECOSYSTEM CHANGES;
20 (V) FLOODING;
21 (VI) SALTWATER INTRUSION;
22 (VII) STORM DAMAGE;
23 (VIII) VECTORBORNE PATHOGENS;
24 (IX) WATERBORNE PATHOGENS; AND
25 (X) WILDFIRES;

SENATE BILL 432 5
1 (2) PAY FOR EXPENSES RELATED TO ANY ACTION BROUGHT BY THE
2 ATTORNEY GENERAL UNDER § 1–307 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE, INCLUDING:
3 (I) INVESTIGATION EXPENSES;
4 (II) LITIGATION EXPENSES; AND
5 (III) TRIAL PREPARATION EXPENSES; AND
6 (3) PAY ADMINISTRATIVE EXPENSES RELATED TO THE DISTRIBUTION
7 OF FUNDS TO PROGRAMS UNDER ITEM (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
8 (G) (1) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL INVEST THE MONEY OF THE FUND
9 IN THE SAME MANNER AS OTHER STATE MONEY MAY BE INVESTED.
10 (2) ANY INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND SHALL BE CREDITED TO
11 THE FUND.
12 (H) EXPENDITURES FROM THE FUND MAY BE MADE ONLY IN ACCORDANCE
13 WITH THE STATE BUDGET.
14 (I) MONEY EXPENDED FROM THE FUND FOR PROGRAMS THAT PREVENT,
15 MITIGATE, OR REPAIR HARMS CAUSED BY CLIMATE CHANGE IS SUPPLEMENTAL TO
16 AND IS NOT INTENDED TO TAKE THE PLACE OF FUNDING THAT OTHERWISE WOULD
17 BE APPROPRIATED FOR THE PROGRAMS.
18 Article – State Finance and Procurement
19 6–226.
20 (a) (2) (i) This paragraph does not apply in fiscal years 2024 through 2028.
21 (ii) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, and unless
22 inconsistent with a federal law, grant agreement, or other federal requirement or with the
23 terms of a gift or settlement agreement, net interest on all State money allocated by the
24 State Treasurer under this section to special funds or accounts, and otherwise entitled to
25 receive interest earnings, as accounted for by the Comptroller, shall accrue to the General
26 Fund of the State.
27 (iii) The provisions of subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph do not
28 apply to the following funds:
29 212. the Department of Social and Economic Mobility Special
30 Fund; [and]

6 SENATE BILL 432
1 213. the Population Health Improvement Fund; AND
2 214. THE CLIMATE CRIMES ACCOUNTABILITY FUND.
3 Article – State Government
4 6–106.2.
5 (a) This section applies to:
6 (1) an action brought or asserted by the State arising from or related to
7 alleged or threatened injuries to the environment, infrastructure, or the natural resources
8 of the State associated with the allision between the vessel known as the Dali and the
9 Francis Scott Key Bridge on March 26, 2024; AND
10 (2) ANY ACTION BROUGHT BY THE ATTORNEY GENERAL UNDER §
11 1–307 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE.
12 (b) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
13 (2) “Proportionate share of liability” means the percentage of comparative
14 responsibility assigned by a judge or jury to a settling party in accordance with this section.
15 (3) “Responsible person” means a person alleged to be liable in an action
16 governed by this section.
17 (c) In an action governed by this section, the judge or jury shall:
18 (1) make a determination of the total liability, including damages, costs,
19 and any other available relief;
20 (2) assign comparative responsibility to each party joined in the action,
21 including all defendants, third–party defendants, intervenors, and any other named party,
22 based on the party’s relative degree of fault or responsibility for the total liability; and
23 (3) if equity requires, determine the liability of a group of related persons
24 on a collective basis.
25 (d) If the State has not obtained complete relief from a responsible person who
26 has resolved the person’s liability to the State in a settlement of an action governed by this
27 section, the State may:
28 (1) continue to pursue an action against any other responsible person who
29 has not resolved the person’s liability to the State; or

SENATE BILL 432 7
1 (2) bring a new action against any other responsible person who has not
2 resolved the person’s liability to the State.
3 (e) Notwithstanding any other provision of State law:
4 (1) the Maryland Uniform Contribution Among Joint Tort–Feasors Act
5 under Title 3, Subtitle 14 of the Courts Article does not apply to an action governed by this
6 section;
7 (2) if a responsible person resolves the person’s liability to the State in a
8 settlement of an action governed by this section, the person may not be liable for claims for
9 noncontractual contribution or indemnity regarding any action or claim resolved in the
10 settlement; and
11 (3) a settlement of an action governed by this section that resolves the
12 liability of a responsible person:
13 (i) does not release from liability any other responsible person
14 except as specifically provided in the terms of the settlement; but
15 (ii) reduces the potential liability of all other responsible persons
16 liable in whole or in part by the larger of:
17 1. the settling person’s proportionate share of liability; or
18 2. the amount the settling person pays to settle the action.
19 (f) This section may not be construed to:
20 (1) impair any express contractual rights;
21 (2) create new types of actions or claims;
22 (3) alter the burden of proof, causation standard, or elements of an action
23 or claim governed by this section; or
24 (4) grant authority to the State or the Attorney General to bring actions or
25 claims not otherwise authorized by law.
26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
27 1, 2026.

